text:
In this task, you will be presented with a sequence of words with unique pitches, then a single word with a unique pitch.

There are two different tasks you may be asked to do.

The first task is to remember only the words in the first sequence, then decide if the following singular word was in the first sequence or not.

The second task is to remember only the pitches in the first sequence, then decide if the pitch of the singular word was in the first sequence or not.

After hearing both the sequence and the singular word, you will be prompted to reply with 'present' or 'absent'.

We will start with some examples.
In this next example, listen to the pitch of the sequence and the following word, then reply if the pitch of the word was 'present' or 'absent'.
In the past example, the pitch of the 4th word was present in the probe stimulus. Let's listen to it again. Don't worry - we know this is challenging!
In the next example, pay special attention to the pitch of the last word in the sequence.
The previous example was 'absent', because the pitch of the single word was different from the pitch of the last word in the sequence. Try a couple more examples on your own.

In this next practice section, you will hear a sequence of words with different pitches, a pause, then a single word. Your task is to determine whether the word itself was present or absent from the sequence.
In the past example, the word of the 4th item in the sequence was the same as the singular word. Let's listen to it again!
In the next example, pay special attention to the 4th word of the sequence.
The previous example was 'present'. Try a couple more examples on your own.

The previous example was 'present'. You are done the introductory trials.

You will now be taken to a practice section with 12 trials. You must get 7/12 trials correct to continue with the rest of the experiment.
